%PDF-1.1\n1 0 obj\n<< /Type /Catalog /Pages 2 0 R >>\nendobj\n2 0 obj\n<< /Type /Pages /Kids [3 0 R] /Count 1 >>\nendobj\n3 0 obj\n<< /Type /Page /Parent 2 0 R /MediaBox [0 0 612 792] /Resources << /Font << /F1 4 0 R >> >> /Contents 5 0 R >>\nendobj\n4 0 obj\n<< /Type /Font /Subtype /Type1 /BaseFont /Helvetica >>\nendobj\n5 0 obj\n<< /Length 2623 >>\nstream\nBT\n/F1 12 Tf\n72 760 Td\n(Armed Forces Wellness Centers ? Overview) Tj\n0 -14 Td\n() Tj\n0 -14 Td\n(What they are) Tj\n0 -14 Td\n(Armed Forces Wellness Centers are health and wellness facilities affiliated with the military that focus on preventive care, health promotion, and non-acute services for uniformed service members and eligible beneficiaries. They are designed to support readiness, resilience, and overall well-being through education, screening, and low-intensity clinical services.) Tj\n0 -14 Td\n() Tj\n0 -14 Td\n(How they work) Tj\n0 -14 Td\n(These centers typically offer services such as health risk assessments, fitness and nutrition counseling, tobacco cessation programs, stress management and behavioral health resources, vaccine and screening clinics, and referrals to higher-level care when needed. They may operate on a walk-in or appointment basis and often coordinate with larger Military Treatment Facilities \\(MTFs\\) to ensure continuity of care.) Tj\n0 -14 Td\n() Tj\n0 -14 Td\n(Ownership and governance) Tj\n0 -14 Td\n(Armed Forces Wellness Centers are generally government-run facilities, operated by the Department of Defense or by individual service branches \\(Army, Navy, Air Force, Space Force\\). In some cases, specific programs or support functions are delivered through contracted partners or local providers under government oversight, but overall governance and funding are governmental. They are not typically private or non-profit community clinics, though partnerships with non-profits or community organizations can occur for specific programs.) Tj\n0 -14 Td\n() Tj\n0 -14 Td\n(Who can use them) Tj\n0 -14 Td\n(Primary users include active-duty service members, and depending on the center, eligible Reserve/National Guard members, dependents, retirees, and other authorized beneficiaries. Access rules vary by location and the policies of the managing military health system.) Tj\n0 -14 Td\n() Tj\n0 -14 Td\n(Why they exist) Tj\n0 -14 Td\n(The primary goals are to maintain force readiness, prevent illness and injury, promote healthy behaviors, and reduce long-term healthcare costs by catching issues early and supporting healthier lifestyles.) Tj\n0 -14 Td\n() Tj\n0 -14 Td\n(Notes and caveats) Tj\n0 -14 Td\n(Terminology and exact services vary by branch and location. Some installations refer to similar programs as "wellness centers," "health promotion clinics," or include wellness services within larger MTFs. If you need a citation or a location-specific profile \\(e.g., what a particular installation calls its center\\), I can look that up.) Tj\n0 -14 Td\nET\nendstream\nendobj\nxref\n0 6\n0000000000 65535 f \n0000000000 00000 n \n0000000010 00000 n \n0000000062 00000 n \n0000000122 00000 n \n0000000251 00000 n \n0000000324 00000 n \n0000000361 00000 n \n0000002984 00000 n \ntrailer\n<< /Size 6 /Root 1 0 R >>\nstartxref\n3003\n%%EOF\n